<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: VENTURA; 'SANDBAG' GUN USED TO SUBDUE PATIENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PAUL ELIAS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Ventura police used a newly acquired "sandbag shotgun" to subdue a mental 
patient menacingly wielding a four-foot metal rod, officers said. 
</P>
<P>
 The 33-year-old man was committing himself voluntarily to the county's 
inpatient psychiatric center about 2:30 p.m. when he suddenly grabbed a fire 
extinguisher and climbed atop the two-story building adjacent to Ventura County 
Medical Center on Loma Vista Road, Officer Mark Stadler said. 
</P>
<P>
 Stadler said when police arrived, the man grabbed the rod and then climbed 
down from the roof. He was shot in the abdomen with a silver-dollar-sized 
sandbag as he stood in the facility's courtyard and waved the rod at officers, 
Stadler said. 
</P>
<P>
 The shotgun blast knocked the wind out of the man and left him with a bruise, 
but otherwise did not injure him, Stadler said. He said it was only the third 
or fourth time Ventura police used the sandbag shotgun, purchased earlier this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
 "This time last year we probably would have had to use batons," Stadler said. 
</P>
<P>
 The man was examined at the medical center and returned to the psychiatric 
unit. Because he is a mental health patient, police refused to release his 
name. He was described as a transient frequently seen in downtown Ventura. PAUL 
ELIAS 
</P>
</TEXT>
