<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: LOS ANGELES; EVIDENCE 
AGAINST EX-OFFICER IN PORNO CASE THROWN OUT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A Superior Court judge threw out evidence Friday against a retired Los Angeles 
police officer accused of taking child pornography from police evidence lockers 
for personal use. 
</P>
<P>
 Judge Robert J. Perry's ruling undercuts the charges against Walter Ray 
Bentley Jr., whose lawyer argued that police failed to explain why they needed 
to search his client's Granada Hills home. 
</P>
<P>
 Prosecutors are now re-examining the case, saying they may have to drop the 
charges. 
</P>
<P>
 The purpose of the search was to look for evidence that Bentley had been 
leaking confidential criminal records to two private investigators, including 
retired Deputy Los Angeles Police Chief Daniel R. Sullivan. Sullivan pleaded no 
contest in September to possessing the confidential files and was fined $5,000 
and placed on a year's probation. Bentley, 47, is also accused of illegally 
accessing police computer files. 
</P>
</TEXT>
