<HEADLINE>
<P>
TOLLWAY FOES SEE BANKRUPTCY AS STOP SIGN; PROTEST: THE 125 PEOPLE IN SUNSET 
OBSERVANCE SAY THE PLANNED ROUTE THROUGH LAGUNA CANYON SHOULD SCRAPPED BECAUSE 
OF COUNTY'S FISCAL WOES. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LESLIE EARNEST and THAO HUA, TIMES STAFF WRITERS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 About 125 people lit candles at sunset Friday in hopes that the county's 
bankruptcy means the end of the day also is near for plans to build a toll road 
through the scenic Laguna Canyon. 
</P>
<P>
 Opponents of the San Joaquin Hills Transportation Corridor gathered about 5:30 
p.m. at Pacific Coast Highway and Broadway for a vigil to send a message to the 
County Board of Supervisors. 
</P>
<P>
 The road "was a preposterous idea to begin with," said Joy Borzellino of Aliso 
Viejo, "but now, (the bankruptcy) makes it even more ludicrous." 
</P>
<P>
 But authorities from the Transportation Corridor Agencies, which is in charge 
of building three Orange County toll roads including the San Joaquin Hills 
corridor, said earlier this week that work will begin as planned in the first 
week of January. 
</P>
<P>
 The 17-mile corridor that will link Newport Beach and San Juan Capistrano is 
needed, Agency spokeswoman Lisa Telles said. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're committed to completing the project," she said. 
</P>
<P>
 Opponents of the toll road say they believe that commitment will wane as money 
is needed elsewhere in the county. About a third of the agency's funding, or 
$311.4 million, is tied up in the county's frozen investment portfolio. As of 
Friday, it was still unclear who will pay for the estimated $2.02-billion loss. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think (the bankruptcy) gives them a chance to re-evaluate priorities," said 
Julie Garner of Garden Grove, "and the toll road should be at the bottom." 
</P>
<P>
 Toll road opponents contend it is only logical for schools and other public 
services to be funded before money is allocated for the controversial roadway, 
which cuts through Laguna Canyon and the Laguna Coast Wilderness Park. And 
although they didn't want to see the county become the largest municipal 
district to declare bankruptcy, they're glad to see the prospect of a toll road 
dim a little. 
</P>
<P>
 Said opponent Max Brown, "This is the only positive side effect." 
</P>
</TEXT>
