<TEXT>
<P>
 Housing Starts Up 6.9% in November: It was the largest increase in eight 
months, as new construction rebounded from the previous month's decline. The 
surprising surge was attributed by analysts to warm weather in the Northeast 
and Midwest.They said they still expect rising mortgage rates to restrain 
single-family construction. "There may be a December pay-back for the temporary 
spike in November housing starts," said economist Jose Rasco of Merrill Lynch & 
Co. in New York. "In any case, the outlook is for a decline in residential 
construction in 1995." The Commerce Department said builders broke ground on 
1.54 million units at a seasonally adjusted annual rate, up from 1.44 million 
in October. Starts are 14.2% higher than they were in the first 11 months of 
1993. 
