<HEADLINE>
<P>
COLLECTIBLES: 1,000 MINIATURE CHAIRS IN MANY FORMS SIT WELL WITH DESIGN 
CONSULTANT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BARBARA MAYER, ASSOCIATED PRESS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 No one would dare to make a chair from beads, theater ticket stubs, plastic 
forks or wheat stalks -- unless it's a miniature chair such as those in George 
Beylerian's collection. 
</P>
<P>
 Beylerian is a design and marketing consultant in the home and office 
furnishings industry in New York. His first miniature came by way of a trade 
promotion during a trip to Italy in the mid-'80s. It sat alone on a shelf in 
his beach house for a couple of years until, when browsing in a curiosity shop, 
he bought a tiny love seat made of twigs. 
</P>
<P>
 He's added about 1,000 chairs since, all carefully documented and displayed on 
custom shelves that line a room in his New York townhouse. 
</P>
<P>
 "The main idea behind my years of collecting is my interest in exploring the 
tremendous variations in the design of a chair," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 The collection ranges from finely crafted early salesman's samples to salt and 
pepper shakers, key chains, pincushions and souvenirs. 
</P>
<P>
 Chairs in miniature have been made for centuries, said David McFadden, curator 
of decorative arts at the Cooper-Hewitt Museum of Design in New York. McFadden 
wrote the text for "Chairmania: Fantastic Miniatures," (Abrams, $19.95), a book 
that shows and tells the story of Beylerian's collection. 
</P>
<P>
 A few of the extant miniatures date to the 17th Century, but most are from the 
19th Century or later. In addition to salesman's samples, there are dollhouse 
chairs and toys and models submitted to the U.S. Patent Office between 1836 and 
1880 to support applications for patents, McFadden said. 
</P>
<P>
 Beylerian has some 19th-Century miniatures in his collection, but most are of 
more recent vintage. He no longer recalls exactly when he acquired his first 
miniature, but he remembers the circumstances: 
</P>
<P>
 "It was given to me as a trade promotion gift during a trip to Udine, Italy, 
the chair manufacturing capital of the world."  
</P>
<P>
 Although he was slow to start collecting, it ultimately added focus to his 
travels. 
</P>
<P>
 "It gave me an excuse to enter any shop, antiques or otherwise, in pursuit of 
my new hobby," Beylerian said. "I had been in chairs all these years, but I had 
never realized that there were so many miniatures. Now, I found them in 
abundant supply, and each find brought a sense of great fulfillment. I became 
passionate about it, and I bought recklessly." 
</P>
<P>
 Eventually he drew his family and friends to the hunt, and artists and 
craftsmen began sending chairs as gifts because they wanted their works to be 
part of the collection. 
</P>
<P>
 "We treat each chair very seriously," Beylerian said. "We give each a number 
and fill in a form indicating condition, materials, where bought and so on." 
</P>
<P>
 He knows about 10 other collectors who, like him, haunt antiques shops and 
junk shops. To some, he said, the thrill of the hunt exceeds the concern for 
price. 
</P>
<P>
 But, he added, "The moment of gratification comes when the seller asks for a 
ridiculously low price, and I know that I am getting a great bargain." 
</P>
</TEXT>
