<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAFETY; GUESTS, GLITTER CAN WREAK HAVOC WITH PET'S HOLIDAY CELEBRATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 This year, try imagining the holidays from your pet's point of view: parties, 
neighbors and friends stopping by, trees, decorations and lights everywhere -- 
even strangers singing carols outside your window. 
</P>
<P>
 Veterinarians tell us dogs and cats crave routine. That means almost 
everything we love about the season creates stress for pets. In addition, the 
holidays can bring special hazards. 
</P>
<P>
 Veterinarians offer a variety of advice to help ensure a safe, happy holiday 
for the family pet. 
</P>
<P>
 Be careful with all that glitters. Cats love playing with tree tinsel. But if 
your pet swallows a strand or two, internal injuries may result. Switch to a 
different decoration if you have rambunctious cats. 
</P>
<P>
 Both dogs and cats may try nibbling on tree lights. To protect everyone from 
electrical shock, install a circuit breaker (sold in hardware stores) at the 
outlet. 
</P>
<P>
 Holiday visitors to your house can unleash deep insecurities in your dog. 
"Dogs are pack animals," says Loren Will, who teaches veterinary medicine at 
Iowa State University. "They're continually attempting to understand their 
place in the pack." 
</P>
<P>
 When Aunt Ruth shows up for a few days, Fido tries to figure out how his place 
in the pack (your family) changes. Some dogs snarl or bark before guests even 
reach the front door. You can help curb this behavior by properly introducing 
each newcomer to your pet. 
</P>
<P>
 One way, Will says, is simply to hold your guest's arm as he or she pets your 
dog. To Fido that signals your acceptance of the new arrival. As a loyal member 
of your pack, your dog is likely to accept the newcomer too. 
</P>
<P>
 Guard that garbage. Holiday cooking can prove an irresistible temptation to 
your dog or cat. Around the holidays, veterinarians treat pets that have 
swallowed everything from string used to tie roasts to the foil that tops 
turkeys in the oven. 
</P>
<P>
 When you have finished cooking, take out the trash right away, he advises, and 
batten down the container to ward off neighborhood scavengers. 
</P>
<P>
 Pets also can be very accomplished beggars, and feeding from the table 
typically encourages bad habits. But be sure you don't reward your pet's 
persistence with chocolate. It can be deadly to dogs, which can't eliminate one 
of the active ingredients in chocolate from their kidneys. If your dog 
"overdoses," he will become hyperactive and his heart rate will increase in 
about three hours. 
</P>
<P>
 Know problem plants. Recent research confirms that poinsettias aren't 
poisonous to dogs or cats, as once was believed. But pets can become seriously 
ill if they nibble on holly or mistletoe. Keep both out of reach. 
</P>
<P>
 Respect your pet's privacy. Sometimes, all the commotion can be too much, 
particularly for older pets. Visiting youngsters who play rough with your pets 
add to the problem. When your dog or cat heads for his "den" beneath the bed or 
in the basement, it's important to respect his privacy, veterinarians say. 
</P>
<P>
 If you want your cat to seek a safe spot that you -- not the cat -- choose, 
veterinarians advise placing a blanket and a couple of toys in an 
out-of-the-way location, such as a closet. Your cat will get the idea. 
</P>
<P>
 Give gifts to pets, but don't give pets as gifts. Present a new toy to your 
pet, and he is likely to act as excited as a child. But the reason, most 
veterinarians agree, probably is because of the attention he's getting, rather 
than the gift itself. 
</P>
<P>
 Veterinarians emphasize that the holidays are a bad time to get or give a new 
pet. Pets acclimate themselves better to new surroundings during a less harried 
time of year, when you'll also have more time to devote to a new pet's needs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
