<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY IN BANKRUPTCY; NEW FOOTHILL RANCH SCHOOL WILL OPEN ON TIME AFTER 
ALL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEFF BEAN, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 What a difference three days make. 
</P>
<P>
 On Tuesday, Saddleback Valley Unified School District officials sent grim word 
to parents that the Jan. 3 opening of Foothill Ranch Elementary School was on 
indefinite hold because of the county's financial quagmire. 
</P>
<P>
 On Friday, the same school district officials changed their minds, saying that 
the contractor has agreed to continue work even though he already is owed 
$118,000, and that district number-crunchers have figured it won't cost that 
much more to open the new facility. 
</P>
<P>
 The news was greeted with cheers by 370 students at Portola Hills Elementary, 
whose classes have been held in portable trailers and who anxiously await a 
move to the new facility after the winter break. They were notified at lunch, 
which turned into an impromptu celebration. 
</P>
<P>
 "We were all smiling and screaming," said Jenna Scherman, a 10-year-old 
fifth-grader. "I was yelling. It's the best. I still can't believe it." 
</P>
<P>
 Jenna's father, Ron Scherman, who had grumbled earlier in the week about the 
delay, struck a far different note Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 "Just the other day I heard rumors that even worse things were going to 
happen, so I was pleasantly surprised," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 District spokeswoman Elaine Carter said the decision was made after officials 
discovered that paying for the trailers at Portola Hills Elementary School 
would cost nearly the same as the extra costs associated with running the new 
school. 
</P>
<P>
 "It just seemed like the practical thing to do," Carter said, "even though 
there will be some additional costs to the district." 
</P>
<P>
 Carter also said that two of the 47 full-time and part-time district workers 
notified this week that Friday would be their last day will be hired back 
because the new school is opening. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's almost a wash to do it," Trustee Dore J. Gilbert said of the financial 
implications to the district for opening the new school versus keeping things 
as they were. "Think how bad you feel when you're ready to move into you new 
home and you get a letter that says, 'Sorry, it's not ready yet.' " 
</P>
</TEXT>
