<HEADLINE>
<P>
LOS ALAMITOS; DOWN WITH DEBT HAS CHANCE TO BE CHAMPION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STACY PIGOTT, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Los Alamitos saved the best for last, as 10 stakes races, including the 
$200,000 Champion of Champions, are scheduled for tonight, the final program of 
the 141-day quarter horse meet. 
</P>
<P>
 Heading the field for the Champion of Champions, tonight's 10th race, is the 
leading contender for world champion honors, Down With Debt.A victory would 
leave the 4-year-old mare undefeated for the year and end Refrigerator's 
two-year world champion reign. 
</P>
<P>
 Owned by George Haddad and trained by Charlie Bloomquist, Down With Debt will 
face a tough field that includes Refrigerator, Brotherly, Femmes Frolic, 
Specially Fast, I Hear A Symphony, Sound Dash, Childish, Sheza First Down and 
Seals. 
</P>
<P>
 Seals, who finished in a dead heat for third in the Z. Wayne Griffin Directors 
Trial, was allowed to enter the Champion of Champions after Avison was 
scratched. The Connie Hall-trained Avison appeared in distress in his last 
start Nov. 11, when he unseated rider Joe Badilla, Jr. 
</P>
<P>
 Tonight's 15-race program also includes six Quarter Horse Breeders Classics 
races, two overnight handicaps for quarter horses and one Arabian stake race. 
</P>
