<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE TIMES 1994 FALL ALL-COUNTY TEAMS; TRITONS' GARDNER A 'CUT ABOVE' ATHLETE OF 
THE YEAR: SIX-FOOT-9 SENIOR GOALKEEPER RAISED SAN CLEMENTE'S DEFENSE TO A 
HIGHER LEVEL. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARTIN BECK, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Gabriel Gardner, San Clemente's 6-foot-9 goalkeeper, had no peers in the 
Southern Section this season. With Gardner putting up a nearly impenetrable 
defense -- he gave up only 4.2 goals per game -- San Clemente advanced to the 
Division I semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
 At his best against the best, Gardner had 20 saves in a regular-season victory 
over eventual Division I champion Long Beach Wilson. 
</P>
<P>
 But sometimes being the most dominant defensive player in the pool wasn't 
enough for Gardner: He wanted to play the field. 
</P>
<P>
 San Clemente Coach Steve Yancey was accommodating; he allowed Gardner to play 
offense late in games the Tritons already had wrapped up and even let him start 
a game against a weaker opponent. 
</P>
<P>
 "I wish sometimes I could have played the field in big games, too," Gardner 
said. "I had so much energy that I felt like I could have turned a guy four 
times if I was setting hole." 
</P>
<P>
 He's probably right. Gardner scored 13 goals this season, including one in the 
final seconds of regulation against El Toro in the South Coast tournament. 
Gardner came out of the goal, looking to make a pass, but finding no one open, 
he winged a shot from mid-pool that skidded into the goal and sent the game 
into overtime. San Clemente went on to win. 
</P>
<P>
 Despite his offensive productivity, Gardner, The Times Orange County player of 
the year, was much more valuable to the Tritons in the goal. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think that a kid like this comes along for our program once in a lifetime," 
Yancey said. "He dominated the sport this year. He was a cut above. 
</P>
<P>
 "We were a decent defensive team, but Gabe made us a great defensive team." 
</P>
<P>
 It was a team that almost got to play for the championship. In the Division I 
semifinal, the Tritons and Wilson were tied, 6-6, late in the fourth quarter 
before Wilson scored a man-advantage goal with 1 minute 8 seconds left and 
added another in the waning seconds. 
</P>
<P>
 It was a crushing loss, but Gardner said he didn't take it as hard as he did 
the semifinal loss that ended his junior year. Some teammates were crying, and 
Gardner said he felt a responsibility to leave a message with the younger 
players. 
</P>
<P>
 "I just told them," Gardner said. " 'Every one of us went out there and gave 
it our all, and it didn't come our way. Remember how this hurts and use it next 
year.' I needed to be the leader and I wanted to show it was all right and that 
we should learn from it." 
</P>
